entry.title: Coastal Flood Advisory issued October 14 at 5:42PM EDT until October 16 at 8:00PM EDT by NWS Newport/Morehead City NC
entry.summary:
* WHAT...For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 6 to 9 feet in the surf zone. For the Beach Hazards Statement, dangerous rip currents, large breaking waves, and strong longshore currents in the surf zone. For the Coastal Flood Advisory, up to 1 to 2 feet of inundation above ground level expected in low-lying areas near shorelines and tidal waterways.
* WHERE...Hatteras Island.
* WHEN...For the High Surf Advisory, until 8 PM EDT Wednesday. For the Beach Hazards Statement, until 8 PM EDT this evening. For the Coastal Flood Advisory, until 8 PM EDT Thursday.
* IMPACTS...Up to 1 to 2 feet of inundation above ground level is possible in low-lying areas near shorelines and tidal waterways resulting in a low threat of property damage. Some roads and low lying property including parking lots, parks, lawns, and homes adjacent to the waterfront will experience shallow flooding. Dangerous swimming and surfing conditions and localized beach erosion. Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away from shore into deeper water. Dangerous shore break can throw a swimmer or surfer head first into the bottom causing neck and back injuries. Strong longshore currents will create dangerous swimming conditions.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The combination of strong onshore winds, high astronomical tides, wave run up, and already battered and weakened dune and other oceanside structures will bring the potential of additional impacts to Hatteras Island, mostly north of Cape Hatteras, around the time of high tide through Thursday. Additionally, minor soundside flooding is expected to last through at least Wednesday.

entry.title: Frost Advisory issued October 14 at 2:36PM PDT until October 15 at 9:00AM PDT by NWS Portland OR
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Temperatures of 32 to 36 degrees will result in frost formation.
* WHERE...South Willamette Valley, North Oregon Coast Range Lowlands, East Central Willamette Valley, and Cowlitz County Lowlands.
* WHEN...From 1 AM to 9 AM PDT Wednesday.
* IMPACTS...Frost could harm sensitive outdoor vegetation. Sensitive outdoor plants may be killed if left uncovered.

entry.summary:
* Winds: A front will bring easterly to southeasterly winds gusting up to 35-45 mph for the Kuskokwim Delta coast. Winds will be strongest Wednesday morning, then decrease by Wednesday afternoon. Confidence is high that this storm will NOT be as strong as former Typhoon Halong.
* Coastal water levels: Little to no coastal flooding is expected with this storm. Along-shore winds could cause water levels to be 1 to 2.5 feet above the normal highest tide line in coastal communities during this morning and Wednesday morning's high tide. Previously flooded and/or low-lying areas may see a small increase in water levels and could be slow to drain.
* Preparedness: Secure loose debris that may be blown about by strong winds. Move items that are near the coast or in low-lying areas further inland or to higher ground. Stay tuned to the forecast. Help share weather information with people whose communication networks may have been affected by the recent storm.

entry.title: Hydrologic Outlook issued October 14 at 5:31AM MDT by NWS Albuquerque NM
entry.summary:
ESFABQ
Rainfall will continue today across northwest New Mexico and southwest Colorado. Rainfall on saturated soils will increase runoff into the San Juan, La Plata and Animas rivers. As a result, high flows will persist through Wednesday. Bankfull conditions are once again expected for the Animas River in Farmington and the San Juan River near Shiprock late today into early Wednesday.
For your safety, stay away from the banks of these rivers. Erosion will make the banks unstable and this fast running water could easily sweep away those distracted near the bank of the river. Avoid any recreational activities on these rivers through at least Wednesday.
Expect rises and impacts to nearby roads and low water crossings. Do not drive through water of unknown depth. The road may not be intact below. Stay aware of any flash flood or river flood warnings that are issued.
